snippet.textDisplay:
The amount of shit they give the one person who was adult enough to do what was needed to get them to their proscribed desired outcome is, I mean I get it but still. Pick your poison guys. Either accept you can't work together as a team well enough to pass these challenges under the conditions you set for yourself and just have fun, stop belly-aching about not winning. Or accept that sometimes, planning and removing options to keep a team focused is what's needed in order to win.

Like, take your pick. Did you want to win or did you want to enjoy the chaos? Both of those are worth-while outcomes and concepts, but you can't belly-ache about how you didn't get both at the same time when you've proven they are often mutually exclusive to one another.

snippet.textDisplay: ngl Ben did an amazing job?? Interesting and original concept, use of the gimmick (which may have otherwise been entirely forgotten...), and still gets flack for not making it broad enough even though that's where they inevitably fail. You can absolutely leave a risotto for minutes at a time and do other stuff, just so long as there's enough liquid, cough Jamie. Normals always panicking about the main and never considering side dishes, either. Also, there always seems to be a feeling of "I want to leave a visible contribution", but that really doesn't define success in the kitchen... continuing someone else's work or brainstorming for the next person is just as valid. Really the only problem is the audience has no idea if the dish was genuinely nice or not.

snippet.textDisplay:
Honestly, y'all are fun to watch, and to me it's more fun to see y'all actually succeed. So here is a thought.

Each person has to make a portion of a combo plate. At the end of thier time, what they made gets covered and the main ingredient is labeled. The following tag ins can smell what's been made, and see what the main ingredient is and has to play off of that. The person in the 5th spot has to assemble and possibly adjust flavors of each to get them to play together. Give each person 15 minutes though, with the option to finish early.

For instance, 1st spot could make a BLT sandwich with maple Brown sugar bacon, cover it and label the closh "bacon". 2nd person makes eggy potato salad with chillies in it, cover and label potato. 3rd makes a cloud egg, covers it and labels it egg. 4th makes a milkshake. 5th has to figure out how to make those flavors pair using sause, presentation, seasonings, or any other tricks they may have and plate it.

Now I have examples of thing that go together. But what if the fist person make Italian meatballs and labeled it beef but everyone else thought it smelled like a burger? Now what happens for to poor Mr 5th spot.

snippet.textDisplay: Mum used to put Vegemite in her Bolognese sauce so I was totally on-board with the marmite. Turns out half of my family is quite intolerant to yeast extract though (yeast is fine) so she doesn't do that anymore. I've had to learn to live without strong umami flavours as I can't tolerate yeast extract, MSG or any of its friends (free glutamates) or flavour enhancers.
